            <div class="rajasthani-border">
                <h1>🏰 The Glorious History of the Badgujar Rajputs</h1>
                <p>The Badgujar Rajputs, a legendary warrior clan, have left an indelible mark on Indian history, particularly in the regions of Rajasthan and Madhya Pradesh. Tracing their lineage to <strong>Lava (Luv)</strong>, the elder son of Bhagwan Shri Ram, the Badgujars ruled over several kingdoms and princely states before India's independence in 1947. Known for their bravery, military prowess, and administrative acumen, the Badgujar Rajputs played a crucial role in shaping the history and culture of central India. Their legacy is not just a tale of kings and kingdoms but a story of resilience, honor, and cultural preservation.</p>
            </div>
            
            <h1>⚔️ Badgujar Rajputs in Madhya Pradesh</h1>
            <div class="rajasthani-pattern">
                <p>Madhya Pradesh was home to several prominent Badgujar Rajput estates, including:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Th.Dhabla Ghosi</strong> - The ancestral seat of our family</li>
                    <li>Dabla Dheer</li>
                    <li>Dadiya Khedi</li>
                    <li>Kamalpur</li>
                    <li>Sadhan Khedi</li>
                </ul>
                <p>One of the most significant branches of the Badgujar Rajputs in the region was the <strong>Raizada branch</strong>, which held a twelve-village estate in Vidisha, granted to Raja Raisingh Badgujar by the Marathas. The main branches of the Badgujar Rajputs in Madhya Pradesh were:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Bhojavat</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Dharmangaj</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Raizada</strong></li>
                </ul>
                <p>Each of these branches contributed to the region's governance and cultural heritage.</p>
            </div>

            <h1>🏯 The Dabla Ghosi Estate: A Symbol of Badgujar Legacy</h1>
            <div class="rajasthani-pattern">
                <p>One of the most notable Badgujar estates was <strong>Th.Dabla Ghosi</strong>, whose history is intertwined with the legacy of <strong>Raja Goga Dev of Rajgarh-Machadi</strong>. His second son, Bhojraj Ji, moved from Machadi to Banawad, where his descendants lived for five generations. The lineage of Dabla Ghosi is as follows:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Rudra Ji → Desh Ji → Madanmal Ji → Gyan Sahay Ji → Khanderay Ji</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Khanderay Ji later moved from Banawad to Kotda in Kheechiwada, where his successors continued to rule. His descendants included Karn Singh Ji, Kumbha Ji, Dashraj Ji, Mohkam Singh Ji, Guman Singh Ji, Raghunath Singh Ji, and Achal Singh Ji.</p>
                <p>Achal Singh Ji had two sons, <strong>Govardhan Singh and Zorawar Singh</strong>. After the defeat of the Marathas by Lord Hastings in 1818, <strong>Dabla Ghosi was declared a guaranteed estate (garanti riyasat)</strong>. The estate received financial support from various rulers:</p>
                
                <table class="history-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr><th>Ruler</th><th>Annual Support (₹)</th></tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Sindhia</td><td>4,000</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Dewas</td><td>100</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Bhopal Darbar</td><td>900</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                
                <p>Additionally, they held a village under Gwalior state, yielding ₹1,050 in revenue. After Rao Govardhan Singh's demise in 1854, his son <strong>Rao Gopal Singh</strong> took over, followed by <strong>Rao Chand Singh</strong> as the ruler of Th. Dhabla Ghosi.</p>
                
                <h3>👑 The Successors of Th.Dhabla Ghosi</h3>
                <p>Rao Chand Singh had five sons:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Rao Hanuvat Singh</li>
                    <li>Zorawar Singh</li>
                    <li><strong>Keshari Singh</strong></li>
                    <li>Hakim Singh</li>
                    <li>Hukam Singh</li>
                </ul>
                <p>When Rao Hanuvat Singh passed away childless, his nephew <strong>Bhupendra Singh</strong>, the son of Keshari Singh, became the ruler of Dabla Ghosi. The family's influence extended to villages like Panda (Tehsil Shujalpur) and Babroda (near Thikana Umri, Guna district), showcasing their enduring legacy.</p>
            </div>
            
            <h1>📜 Suryavanshi Badgujar Rajput Lineage Details</h1>
            <div class="rajasthani-border">
                <table class="history-table">
                    <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Category</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>Dynasty</td><td>Suryavansh</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>Gotra</td><td>Kashyap</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>Ancestral Land</td><td>Ayodhya</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>Branch</td><td>Maradadhvani</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>Sutra</td><td>Katyayani</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>Guru</td><td>Vashishta</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>Veda</td><td>Yajurveda</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>River</td><td>Saryu</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>Clan Goddess</td><td>Ashavari Mata</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>Sword</td><td>Sakal (Vijayalakshmi)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>11</td><td>Flag Symbol</td><td>Panchayan</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>12</td><td>Sacred Tree</td><td>Ashoka</td></tr>
